---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Aside from '../../../components/Aside.astro';
import { streamsSidebar } from '../../../data/streams-sidebar';
import { Code } from 'astro:components';
---

<DocsLayout title="Operators" sidebar={streamsSidebar} description="Transform and filter operators in Streams">

<h1>Operators</h1>

<p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
  Every operator takes a stream and returns a new stream. Chain them freely.
</p>

    <h2>steady</h2>

    <p>Not an operator on an existing stream — a factory for a <code>Stream&lt;T&gt;</code> that always
        holds the same value. It never changes and never notifies beyond the initial delivery.</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.streams.steady

val pi = steady(3.14)

println(pi())  // 3.14

// Subscribers are called once with the value and never again
pi.subscribeToStream { println(it) }  // prints "3.14"`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <Aside>Handy when an API wants a <code>Stream&lt;T&gt;</code> but you only have a plain value — no
        need to spin up a <code>StreamSource</code> just to never update it.
    </Aside>

    <h2>map</h2>

<p>Transform each value:</p>

<Code code={`val source = StreamSource(5)
val doubled = source.map { it * 2 }

println(doubled())  // 10

source(10)
println(doubled())  // 20`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<h2>onEach</h2>

<p>Execute a side effect for each value without changing it. Useful for logging:</p>

<Code code={`val source = StreamSource(1)

val stream = source
    .onEach { println("Saw: ${'$'}it") }
    .map { it * 10 }`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<h2>indexed</h2>

<p>Pairs each value with its index (starting at 0):</p>

<Code code={`val source = StreamSource("a")
val indexed = source.indexed()

// Pair(0, "a"), then Pair(1, "b"), Pair(2, "c")...`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<h2>filter</h2>

    <p>Only pass values matching a predicate. Since streams always have a value, you must provide an initial value for
        when nothing matches yet:</p>

    <Aside>This is the "always has a value" contract showing its teeth. You pay with one extra parameter. Honestly, it's
        worth it.
    </Aside>

<Code code={`val source = StreamSource(3)

val big = source.filter(initial = 0) { it > 10 }
println(big())  // 0

source(20)
println(big())  // 20

source(5)
println(big())  // 20 (keeps last matching value)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

    <h3>Nullable filter</h3>

    <p>When you don't want to provide an initial value, use the nullable variant. It returns <code>null</code> until a
        value matches:</p>

    <Code code={`val source = StreamSource(3)
val big = source.filter { it > 10 }  // Stream<Int?>

println(big())  // null (nothing matched yet)

source(20)
println(big())  // 20`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h3>filterNotNull</h3>

    <p>Remove nulls from a nullable stream. The result is still <code>Stream&lt;String?&gt;</code> because the current
        value may be null if no non-null value has arrived yet:</p>

    <Code code={`val source = StreamSource<String?>(null)
val safe = source.filterNotNull()  // Stream<String?>

println(safe())  // null (no non-null value yet)

source("hello")
println(safe())  // "hello"

source(null)
println(safe())  // "hello" (keeps last non-null)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h3>filterIsInstance</h3>

    <p>Filter by type, using Kotlin's reified type parameter:</p>

    <Code code={`val source = StreamSource<Any>("text")
val strings = source.filterIsInstance<String>()  // Stream<String?>

println(strings())  // "text"

source(42)
println(strings())  // "text" (42 is not a String, keeps last match)

source("new text")
println(strings())  // "new text"`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

<h2>distinct</h2>

<p>Only publish when the value actually changes:</p>

<Code code={`val source = StreamSource(1)
val distinct = source.distinct()

val received = mutableListOf<Int>()
distinct.subscribeToStream { received.add(it) }

source(1)  // same — skipped
source(2)  // different — published
source(2)  // same — skipped
source(3)  // different — published

// received = [1, 2, 3]`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<p>Use <code>distinctStrict()</code> for reference equality (<code>!==</code>) instead of structural equality (<code>!=</code>).</p>

<h2>fallback</h2>

<p>Replace null values with a default:</p>

<Code code={`val source = StreamSource<String?>(null)

val safe = source.fallbackTo("default")
println(safe())  // "default"

source("hello")
println(safe())  // "hello"

// Or compute the fallback dynamically
val computed = source.fallbackBy { "fallback-value" }`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark" />

<div class="not-prose mt-8 flex gap-4">
  <a href="/ultra/streams/combining" class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-brand-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-brand-500 transition-colors">
    Combining &amp; accumulating &rarr;
  </a>
</div>

</DocsLayout>
